            <Text>Capital Boost’s Accommodation Offering Was Likely Unreasonable, As The Prayer Break Terms Did Not Provide Barat Sufficient Opportunity To Fulfill His Religious Duties. The Boiler Room Also Appears Questionable As An Adequate Prayer Space Even With Improvements.
A reasonable accommodation requires that the employee is given the ability to fulfill their religious duties and practices. However, this accommodation does have to be a “total” accommodation, nor must it be the preferred option for the employee Tabura v. Kellogg USA, 880 F.3d 544, 550 (10th Cir. 2018). The court appears to define reasonable as an accommodation that, at a minimum, allows the employee the opportunity to fully resolve the conflict by their own efforts. If the employee would be unable to resolve the conflict between religious duties and  work duties, it is not reasonable CASE; However, if the facts would support a finding that the employee would be able to fulfill both duties though additional efforts of their own, then the accommodation would be considered reasonable even if the accommodation is a minor one on the part of the employer. TWA v. Hardison, 432 U.S. 63, 80 (1977).
The controlling case for this is Tabura v. Kellogg USA, in which two Seventh Day Adventists had been accommodated by their employer by allowing the pair to swap shift or used paid time off to avoid working on otherwise mandatory Saturday shifts. The court reversed a summary judgment ruling in favor of Kellogg as it determined that the the reasonableness of the accommodation need be determined by a jury. The issue of fact in contention was not if Kellogg had completely eliminated the conflict in duties, but rather, if the employees were able to exercise reasonable effort to eliminate the issue through their own bargaining. Similar to this the court more directly —— A case similar to the fact pattern at hand is Christmon v. B&amp;B Airparts, Inc., 735 F. App'x 510, 512 (10th Cir. 2018). While  —
When applied to Capital Boost are Barat, there are some key facts that would likely preclude Capital Boost from succeeding in a claim that the accommodation was reasonable. Capital Boost’s accommodation for Barat, was allowing prayer in the boiler room, using break time alloted by the written rules. This did not include periods of time where staff meeting were occurring, which Barat Would be required to attend in full. 


