Notice: PLEASE REFER TO FEDERAL RULES OF APPELLATE PROCEDURE RULE 32.1 GOVERNING THE CITATION TO UNPUBLISHED OPINIONS.
Subsequent History: US Supreme Court certiorari denied by Christmon v. B&amp;B Airparts, Inc., 2018 U.S. LEXIS 6313 (U.S., Oct. 29, 2018)
Prior History:  [**1] D.C. No. 2:16-CV-02341-CM. (D. Kan.).
Christmon v. B&amp;B Airparts, Inc., 2017 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 140627 (D. Kan., Aug. 31, 2017)
Case Summary




Overview
HOLDINGS: [1]-In a former employee's religious discrimination case under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, the district court did not err in considering a deposition transcript submitted by the employer. The employer filed the certification required by Fed. R. Civ. P. 30(f)(1) when the employee raised the issue; [2]-The employee's claim failed because allowing the employee to skip mandatory Saturday overtime shifts after he explained his religious concern constituted a reasonable accommodation. The employer was not required to offer the employee his preferred accommodation of making up the overtime hours on Sunday.
Outcome
Judgment affirmed.
