4 The District Court voiced concern that if it did not find an undue hardship in such circumstances, accommodation of religious observances might impose &quot;'a priority of the religious over the secular'&quot; and thereby raise significant questions as to the constitutional validity of the statute under the .  , quoting Edwards &amp; Kaplan, Religious Discrimination and the Role of Arbitration Under Title VII, 69 Mich. L. Rev. 599, 628 (1971).
