            <Text>Capital Boost Likely Failed To Reasonably Accommodate Barat’s Religious Practices In Its Offer. However, it is more likely than not that Barat’s Failure to Engage in the Bilateral Negotiation Process Undermines His Claim.
	Within the 10th circuit, a reasonable accommodation is an ad hoc determination. The facts of the case are evaluated to determine if the accommodation offered allows the employee to practice their religious practices despite the normal rules of the employer Tabura v. Kellogg USA, 880 F.3d 544, 550 (10th Cir. 2018). 
This subsection evaluates whether Capital Boost shifted the burden after Barat established a prima facie case, and, on the premise that it did, whether Barat then met his obligation to propose an alternate accommodations.

