Prior History:  [**1] Appeal from the United States District Court for the District of Utah. (D.C. No. 1:14-CV-00014-TC-PMW).
Tabura v. Kellogg USA, Inc., 194 F. Supp. 3d 1188, 2016 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 88363 (D. Utah, July 7, 2016)
Case Summary




Overview
HOLDINGS: [1]-Where employees' religious practice of weekly observing the Sabbath by refraining from work from sundown Friday through sunset Saturday conflicted with their employer's requirement that its production employees work every other Saturday, disputed issues of material fact remained, requiring resolution by the trier of fact, in the employees' Title VII suit; [2]-Title VII required the employer reasonably to accommodate the employees' religious practice, if the employer could do so without incurring undue hardship to its business, but whether the employer had reasonably accommodated the employees' Sabbath observance by a combination of allowing them to use their vacation and other paid time off, as well as permitting them to swap shifts with other employees, and, if not, whether the employer could do so without undue hardship, required resolution by the trier of fact.
Outcome
Decision reversed; case remanded.
LexisNexis® Headnotes





Civil Procedure &gt; ... &gt; Summary Judgment &gt; Appellate Review &gt; Standards of Review
HN1  Appellate Review, Standards of Review
An appellate court reviews a district court's summary judgment decisions de novo.

Civil Procedure &gt; ... &gt; Summary Judgment &gt; Entitlement as Matter of Law &gt; Genuine Disputes
